<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-962-012  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 962 012.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  Dec 1989 v26 n12 p34(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Next-generation spacecraft control.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bell, Trudy E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Gamma Ray Observatory, Hubble Space Telescope, and Galileoprobe are three of seven spacecraft launched or scheduled forlaunch in 1990, all containing electronic control systems vastlymore sophisticated than those of earlier generations.andP;  Thirty-sixmajor missions are planned through 1994.andP;  The Hubble SpaceTelescope employs artificial intelligence and new on-board controlsystems to make some 3,000 exposures of several hundred celestialtargets.andP;  The Gamma Ray Observatory holds six tons of detectorsand electronics to measure gamma rays from any source.andP;  TheGalileo probe will make the first entry into a gaseous planetaryatmosphere, in this case Jupiter.andP;  Other projects includeMagellan, Cosmic Background Explorer, Ulysses, and Astro-1.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Space ExplorationElectronicsAnalysisGamma Ray Observatory (Artificial satellite)Hubble Space TelescopeGalileo ProjectMagellan (Space probe)Cosmic Background Explorer (Artificial satellite)Ulysses (Space probe)Astro-1 (Space probe).andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Gamma Ray Observatory spacecraft includes four scientificinstruments. (chart)Major space science missions, 1989-90: instruments, contractors,etc. (table)Galileo probe descent module has two shelves to separateinstruments. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>